# quick and dirty, a truncated normal distribution to work on the solution set

z <- rnorm(n=3000, mean=0.2)
z <- data.frame(1:3000, z)
names(z) <- list("ID", "myVar")
z <- z[z$myVar > 0,]

Plot normal probability density

meanML <- normPars$estimate["mean"]
sdML <- normPars$estimate["sd"]
xval <- seq(0,max(z$myVar), len=length(z$myVar))
stat <- stat_function(aes(x=xval, y=..y..), fun=dnorm,
                      color="red", n=length(z$myVar), 
                      args=list(mean=meanML, sd=sdML))
p1 + stat
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Plot exponential probability density

expoPars <- fitdistr(z$myVar, "exponential")

stat2 <- stat_function(aes(x=xval, y=..y..), fun=dexp,
                       color="blue", n=length(z$myVar),
                       args=list(rate=rateML))
p1 + stat + stat2

The two histograms look very similar, but my real dataset has more variation than the simulated dataset. The probability density is higher in the simulated dataset for values around the mean. There are also fewer outliers and gaps in the simulated dataset than in my real dataset. I think the simulated datasets histogram is doing a good job representing the probability distribution of my real data, but the standard deviation calculated by the normal probability distribution (20297) was lower than the actual calculated value (20507) and since the simulated dataset was created based on the probability values and not the real calculated values, this could explain the lack of variation seen in my simulated histogram as compared to the higher variation seen in my real data histogram. If I were to alter the parameters of the simulated dataset, I would use the real calculated standard deviation instead of that of the model to try to make the simulated dataset more realistic.
